                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "id": "iYSBx",
                          "name": "sumP1",
                          "fill": "#374151",
                          "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                          "width": "fill_container",
                          "content": "The April 28 meeting opened with a brief special session: council voted 4-2 to authorize an outside investigator and outside counsel for a second alleged ethics violation involving Councilmember Sharon Davis (excused for the vote). Councilmembers Lovisone and Griffith dissented, asking that findings from the first, still-pending investigation be released before opening a new one.",
                          "lineHeight": 1.6,
                          "fontFamily": "Inter",
                          "fontSize": 14,
                          "fontWeight": "normal"
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "id": "TcsVd",
                          "name": "sumP2",
                          "fill": "#374151",
                          "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                          "width": "fill_container",
                          "content": "The bulk of the evening was a workshop on solid waste, recycling fees, and composting. Council reached informal consensus on a 5-cent program fee increase, maintaining the $1.06 enterprise fee, and the staff's stepwise composting plan: a near-term scraps-managed drop-off pilot plus composting as a bid alternate in the 2028 hauler RFP. Mayor Pro Tem Moorman pushed unsuccessfully for a faster citywide opt-out program funded by the incoming Extended Producer Responsibility (EPR) recycling refund.",
                          "lineHeight": 1.6,
                          "fontFamily": "Inter",
                          "fontSize": 14,
                          "fontWeight": "normal"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
