                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "ZUInN",
              "name": "Lead Story",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "layout": "vertical",
              "gap": 18,
              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "qY4h9",
                  "fill": "#3b5bdb",
                  "content": "BRIEFING · WILDFIRE PREPAREDNESS",
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 11,
                  "fontWeight": "700",
                  "letterSpacing": 2
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "T0DIhI",
                  "fill": "#111827",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "How Arvada plans for a wildfire — briefed by Fire Chief Greg Smith",
                  "lineHeight": 1.15,
                  "fontFamily": "Playfair Display",
                  "fontSize": 34,
                  "fontWeight": "700"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "H4K9z1",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "This is a study session, not a vote. Council heard a one-hour briefing from Arvada Fire Protection District on wildfire risk modeling, evacuation planning, and where the city's $2.3M FEMA grant will be spent. The session was observation-only — no public comment was taken — and council asked questions but made no decisions.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 18,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "GgRw2",
                  "name": "Pull Quote 1",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "layout": "vertical",
                  "gap": 12,
                  "padding": [
                    16,
                    40
                  ],
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "xgJWu",
                      "fill": "#111e5c",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "“If a fire starts in the Standley Lake drainage on a red-flag-warning day, we have roughly 90 minutes before homes in the highest-risk zone are threatened. That window is what every piece of this plan is built around.”",
                      "lineHeight": 1.35,
                      "fontFamily": "Playfair Display",
                      "fontSize": 26,
                      "fontWeight": "normal",
                      "fontStyle": "italic"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "FYkBj",
                      "fill": "#6b7280",
                      "content": "— Fire Chief Greg Smith, Arvada Fire Protection District",
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 13,
                      "fontWeight": "600",
                      "letterSpacing": 1
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "HmCWw",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "What council learned: Arvada's wildfire risk has shifted west and north over the last decade, driven by the same hot-and-dry trend that informed the city's drought response plan. Chief Smith walked council through Arvada Fire's updated WUI (wildland-urban interface) risk map, which now extends the highest-risk zone an additional 1.4 miles east into neighborhoods that had been classified as moderate risk in the 2018 study. The shift, he said, is driven primarily by fuel-load changes — denser undergrowth in the foothills following two below-average snow years — rather than ignition probability.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "cH6su",
                  "name": "ldsBody2",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Where the FEMA money goes: The city's $2.3M FEMA Building Resilient Infrastructure & Communities (BRIC) grant funds three things. First, a defensible-space rebate program for homeowners in the highest-risk WUI zones — up to $1,500 per parcel for tree thinning, ember-resistant vents, and metal roofing upgrades. Second, two new mobile water-pump units capable of drawing from non-hydrant sources. Third, a community alert system that integrates with existing emergency notification platforms. Chief Smith said rebate applications would open within 60 days of the grant agreement's signature, currently slated for early June.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "KmSBE",
                  "name": "ldsBody3",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Open issues: Most evacuation bottlenecks identified in the 2024 tabletop exercise have now been addressed. The remaining one — Indiana Street north of 80th — is in active design with CDOT and could be widened by late 2027. Chief Smith also flagged a gap in mutual-aid coverage on the city's northwest edge, where Arvada Fire's response time depends on West Metro Fire's deployment posture. A revised mutual-aid agreement is in negotiation but not yet signed; council asked staff to bring back an update when the language is final.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "eCTjw",
                  "name": "sources",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "fill": "#f5f3ff",
                  "cornerRadius": 4,
                  "stroke": {
                    "thickness": 1,
                    "fill": "#c4b5fd"
                  },
                  "layout": "vertical",
                  "gap": 6,
                  "padding": [
                    14,
                    18
                  ],
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "gp08F",
                      "fill": "#5b21b6",
                      "content": "SOURCES & RESOURCES",
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 10,
                      "fontWeight": "700",
                      "letterSpacing": 2
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "DYZD7",
                      "fill": "#2f4ac7",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "↗ Apex Fire Risk Atlas (Arvada Fire Protection District) · CDPHE WUI guidelines · BRIC grant award letter (FEMA) · 2024 evacuation tabletop after-action memo · Mutual-aid agreement draft · Watch the full briefing from 8:42",
                      "lineHeight": 1.6,
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 12,
                      "fontWeight": "600",
                      "letterSpacing": 0.3
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "XqCoj",
              "name": "Briefing — Utility Rate Study",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "layout": "vertical",
              "gap": 18,
              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "B2Jj0",
                  "fill": "#3b5bdb",
                  "content": "BRIEFING · 2026 UTILITY RATE STUDY",
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 11,
                  "fontWeight": "700",
                  "letterSpacing": 2
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "s5c5A",
                  "fill": "#111827",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Water rates could rise 4–6% a year — but the EPR refund could offset most of it",
                  "lineHeight": 1.15,
                  "fontFamily": "Playfair Display",
                  "fontSize": 34,
                  "fontWeight": "700"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "DF0kB",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Water-rate consultant Stantec presented preliminary results from the 2026 utility rate study. The headline number — a 4–6% annual increase over five years to keep capital reserves at policy minimums — would translate to roughly $4–$6 per month on the typical residential bill. No decisions were made tonight; council asked staff to return with a refined recommendation that pairs the rate study with a customer-communication plan.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 18,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "PuyZd",
                  "name": "Pull Quote",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "layout": "vertical",
                  "gap": 12,
                  "padding": [
                    16,
                    40
                  ],
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "XqReW",
                      "fill": "#111e5c",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "“The reason we're surfacing this now, rather than at next year's budget cycle, is that the EPR refund and the rate increase will hit residents' bills in roughly the same six-month window. That's a communication problem we have to solve now, not later.”",
                      "lineHeight": 1.35,
                      "fontFamily": "Playfair Display",
                      "fontSize": 26,
                      "fontWeight": "normal",
                      "fontStyle": "italic"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "GqWqL",
                      "fill": "#6b7280",
                      "content": "— Finance Director Bryan Archer · 1:09:18 in the meeting",
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 13,
                      "fontWeight": "600",
                      "letterSpacing": 1
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "p0Qc6k",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "What was presented: Stantec's analysis runs through 2031. The 4–6% per-year band reflects two scenarios — a baseline case that maintains the city's current minimum reserve policy and a stress case that funds an accelerated lead-service-line replacement program. Both scenarios account for declining per-capita water use (down 11% since 2018) and the rising cost of treated water from Denver Water under Arvada's wholesale agreement, which steps up under a cost-of-service formula every three years.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "WLSAI",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "How residents would see it: The proposed increase would translate to roughly $4.10–$6.20 per month on the typical residential bill for a household using 4,000 gallons. Stantec recommended tiered pricing that protects low-volume users (under 2,000 gallons per month) from the full increase — a structural change from Arvada's current uniform rate. The recommendation is in the consultant's report but has not been adopted; council will see a full rate ordinance at a future business meeting where public comment will be taken.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "oPFqj",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "The offsetting factor: The EPR (Extended Producer Responsibility) recycling refund — a separate utility — starts hitting customer bills this fall and will return $5–7 per month to most households. Stantec noted that the net effect for a typical residential customer in 2027 would be approximately neutral, though it varies sharply by water use. Multi-family properties and water-intensive commercial customers see no EPR offset since the refund is residential-only. Archer flagged this asymmetry as the most important caveat in the rate-study conversation.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "WTfNG",
                  "name": "sources",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "fill": "#f5f3ff",
                  "cornerRadius": 4,
                  "stroke": {
                    "thickness": 1,
                    "fill": "#c4b5fd"
                  },
                  "layout": "vertical",
                  "gap": 6,
                  "padding": [
                    14,
                    18
                  ],
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "hUjGW",
                      "fill": "#5b21b6",
                      "content": "SOURCES & RESOURCES",
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 10,
                      "fontWeight": "700",
                      "letterSpacing": 2
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "l261Kl",
                      "fill": "#2f4ac7",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "↗ Stantec 2026 Rate Study (full PDF) · Arvada water rate history (open-data portal) · EPR refund FAQ (CDPHE) · Denver Water wholesale agreement · Lead-service-line replacement program memo · Watch the full briefing from 1:08:30",
                      "lineHeight": 1.6,
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 12,
                      "fontWeight": "600",
                      "letterSpacing": 0.3
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "frame",
              "id": "KJ74K",
              "name": "Briefing — Sustainable Energy Plan",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "layout": "vertical",
              "gap": 18,
              "children": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "wLJRn",
                  "fill": "#3b5bdb",
                  "content": "BRIEFING · SUSTAINABLE ENERGY PLAN",
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 11,
                  "fontWeight": "700",
                  "letterSpacing": 2
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "tqZbU",
                  "fill": "#111827",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Five-year scorecard: on pace for buildings, ahead on city operations, behind on transportation",
                  "lineHeight": 1.15,
                  "fontFamily": "Playfair Display",
                  "fontSize": 34,
                  "fontWeight": "700"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "T8b4VM",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Sustainability Manager Diana Sander presented the five-year scorecard for Arvada's 2021 Sustainable Energy Plan. Of the plan's three community-wide targets — 40% renewable electricity by 2030, 25% reduction in transportation emissions, and net-zero municipal operations by 2035 — Arvada is on pace for two and behind on one. Council asked staff to return with a transportation-focused policy package, likely at a workshop later this year.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 18,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "bV8iN",
                  "name": "Pull Quote",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "layout": "vertical",
                  "gap": 12,
                  "padding": [
                    16,
                    40
                  ],
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "yZQOV",
                      "fill": "#111e5c",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "“The biggest gap in our scorecard is transportation. The plan modeled 18% of new vehicles registered in Arvada as EVs by 2025. The actual number is 11. That's a policy problem, not a market problem.”",
                      "lineHeight": 1.35,
                      "fontFamily": "Playfair Display",
                      "fontSize": 26,
                      "fontWeight": "normal",
                      "fontStyle": "italic"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "l1wziT",
                      "fill": "#6b7280",
                      "content": "— Sustainability Manager Diana Sander · 1:43:50 in the meeting",
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 13,
                      "fontWeight": "600",
                      "letterSpacing": 1
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "gRlRK",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "What was presented: Sander walked council through the scorecard's three community-wide targets and the underlying GHG inventory that powers the year-by-year measurements. The 2024 inventory — the most recent — shows total community-wide emissions down 14% from the 2018 baseline, but the reductions are uneven across sectors. Building energy and municipal operations are pulling the average down; transportation is pulling it back up.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "xmxB1",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Where Arvada is ahead: Municipal operations are tracking ahead of the 2035 net-zero target thanks to the solar carport program installed at the rec center and three city facilities in 2024. That program now offsets roughly 38% of municipal electricity demand, ahead of the 25% scorecard milestone. Building-energy emissions are also on pace — partly because of the 2022 building code update requiring electric-ready infrastructure in new construction, and partly because Xcel's grid mix has shifted faster than the plan modeled, with coal generation falling out of the merit order ahead of schedule.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "dYo69",
                  "fill": "#374151",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Where Arvada is behind: Transportation is the laggard. The plan assumed 18% of new vehicles registered in Arvada would be EVs by 2025; the actual figure is 11%. Sander attributed the gap to charging-infrastructure access in multi-family housing and the absence of a curbside-charging permit pathway. She signaled that staff will return with a transportation-electrification policy package — likely including curbside-charging pilot rules and a fleet electrification timeline — at a workshop later this year. Council asked staff to coordinate that work with the Sustainable Energy Plan's full refresh, which is due in 2027.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.65,
                  "fontFamily": "Newsreader",
                  "fontSize": 17,
                  "fontWeight": "normal"
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "ge9PE",
                  "name": "sources",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "fill": "#f5f3ff",
                  "cornerRadius": 4,
                  "stroke": {
                    "thickness": 1,
                    "fill": "#c4b5fd"
                  },
                  "layout": "vertical",
                  "gap": 6,
                  "padding": [
                    14,
                    18
                  ],
                  "children": [
                    {
